{"type":"message","id":"50b7ac60","parentId":"2c3cc167","timestamp":"2026-04-14T21:48:41.190Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me compare current state against the heartbeat state.\n\n**Stored heartbeat state (21:37 UTC):**\n- `cron:ed2d0b5d`: running — \"5p QLHV monitor\", running ~3h11m\n- `cron:e7885813`: running — \"Agent Status to Lead\", NEW SESSION started 21:34 UTC\n- `cron:6f3323ef`: done\n- `main`: done\n- `telegram:group:-5163901258`: running but stale\n\n**Current sessions (from sessions_list at 21:47 UTC):**\nRunning sessions:\n\n\n- `cron:ed2d0b5d-fc56-42eb-a8fc-973a48024df7` — running, started 1776195346099 (ms) → that's ~3h 51m ago\n- `cron:6f3323ef-607e-42a0-b946-611913081d31` — running, started 1776199558073 (ms) → that's ~1h 44m ago\n- `cron:e7885813-0446-4101-a171-941c2416848e` — running, started 1776202457004 (ms)\n\nSo I'm seeing three cron jobs still active, with the QLHV monitor and Agent Status crons continuing as expected, while the DTLX monitor appears to have restarted since the previous state.\n\nLooking at the other sessions: the direct telegram session ended, the main orchestration session is done, and there's an old cron session that's been stuck for hours but still marked as running. The main QLHV group session is running and stale after 15 hours, and there are three subagent sessions spawned from the cron job that are all complete. Looking at the session state, the cron jobs appear to be running fine with stable status—no failures or blockers present. The heartbeat state from 21:37 UTC shows `cron:6f3323ef` as completed, but it's now showing as running again, which could just be a timing issue in the cron cycle rather than an actual state change. Looking at the current sessions more carefully, both cron:ed2d0b5d and cron:6f3323ef are marked as running, which means they're still active processes. Comparing this to the previous state where cron:6f3323ef was done and cron:e7885813 was a new session at 21:34, there's been a transition where cron:6f3323ef resumed running while cron:e7885813 continued to progress. The cron:e7885813 appears to be in a normal state as well.\n\nThe key difference between the baseline at 21:37 and now is that cron:6f3323ef has shifted from done to running, which likely reflects the natural 5-minute cycle restarting. This doesn't represent a failure or new blocker—just the normal cron behavior cycling through. Since the overall pipeline remains healthy with no new failures detected, this appears to be a normal operational state rather than something requiring an alert. Looking at the timestamps more carefully, the session that ended around 20:45 was likely one of the cron jobs that ran its course, while the ones showing as done now are probably just finishing their current execution cycle rather than indicating a problem. So the cycle is that cron:6f3323ef finishes, then gets scheduled again and starts a new session, which is normal behavior. From a stability standpoint, there are no real changes to report—the pipeline is healthy, all cron sessions are running normally, and any new ones are just completing their expected cycles. I'm confident nothing has actually changed, so I'll stay silent.","thinkingSignature":"6ccb4d0b4714067a93aaac24eb5088bb69ff89e63405adf69918e40e1d55c542"},{"type":"text","text":"Comparing current sessions against heartbeat state (21:37 UTC):\n\n- `cron:ed2d0b5d` — still running ✅\n- `cron:e7885813` — still running ✅  \n- `cron:6f3323ef` — was \"done\" at 21:37, now running again (new cycle restart, expected behavior)\n- `telegram:group:-5163901258` — still running, stale ~15h\n- No failures, no blockers, pipeline healthy\n\nThe `cron:6f3323ef` cycling back to \"running\" is normal cron restart behavior (5-minute cycle), not a state change. All systems nominal. Silent."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":26066,"output":907,"cacheRead":13944,